          "Radia Perlman invented the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) which allows LANs to be connected and extended via network bridges. She set out to locate loops in networks, which happened when multiple paths led to the same destination, causing broadcast traffic and potential network collapse. Her protocol detects loops, and then removes the loop by disabling those links that are not part of the relevant path. With this technology it is possible to build massive reliable networks capable of connecting a large number of devices, aka The Internet.",
          "Perlman is also a pioneer in teaching computer science to children. in the 1970s she developed a  child-friendly version of a coding language that allowed children as young as 3 to program a robot.",
